{"id":321,"date":"2018-04-11T17:51:51","date_gmt":"2018-04-11T23:51:51","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/?p=321"},"modified":"2018-04-11T18:50:15","modified_gmt":"2018-04-12T00:50:15","slug":"thermostat-web-app","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/byu-iot-lab\/thermostat-web-app\/","title":{"rendered":"Thermostat Web App"},"content":{"rendered":"<h2>A web-based interface for controlling the IoT thermostat<\/h2>\n<p>The API-based IoT thermostat system I have been working on has four main components:<\/p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/byu-iot-lab\/hvac-controller\/\">HVAC Controller<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/byu-iot-lab\/hvac-software\/\">Software<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/byu-iot-lab\/hvac-api\/\">API<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/byu-iot-lab\/temperature-sensor\/\">Temperature Sensor, Software, and API<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/byu-iot-lab\/thermostat-api\/\">Thermostat Logic, and API<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Interface for controlling thermostat<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n<p>This post is about the fourth and final component: the web app for controlling the thermostat. Technically the IoT thermostat can function completely without this component (intentionally so), but it provides a convenient interface for the user to interact with the different APIs associated with the IoT thermostat. In fact, multiple interfaces could be created, such as a mobile app or an alternative web app. The thermostat web app is essentially just a front end interface for the thermostat API.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/whites-honeywell-programmable-thermostats-rth6350d-64_1000-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" class=\"alignright wp-image-326 size-medium\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/whites-honeywell-programmable-thermostats-rth6350d-64_1000-300x300.jpg 300w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/whites-honeywell-programmable-thermostats-rth6350d-64_1000-150x150.jpg 150w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/whites-honeywell-programmable-thermostats-rth6350d-64_1000-768x768.jpg 768w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/whites-honeywell-programmable-thermostats-rth6350d-64_1000.jpg 1000w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>A traditional thermostat is interfaced with physical buttons and a display. The thermostat web app serves to emulate this functionality by providing virtual buttons and displaying current information.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h2>Web App<\/h2>\n<p>I implemented the web app in javascript and used jquery to make requests to the APIs. The app is pretty simple and the current design is a little ugly. Hopefully I can find time to make the UI look a little nicer in the future. Regardless, the app is a functional interface for controlling the IoT thermostat design that I have been building.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Web app url:<\/strong> <a href=\"http:\/\/thermostat.zachbrogan.com\">thermostat.zachbrogan.com<\/a><\/p>\n<p><strong>Web app code:<\/strong> <a href=\"http:\/\/github.com\/zbrogz\/thermostat\">github.com\/zbrogz\/thermostat<\/a><\/p>\n<p><strong>Language:\u00a0<\/strong>Javascript, HTML<\/p>\n<p><strong>Server:\u00a0<\/strong>Amazon EC2 Ubuntu instance running NGINX<\/p>\n<p><strong>Domain:\u00a0<\/strong>BYU Domains (*.zachbrogan.com)<\/p>\n<p>The web app provides the following features:<\/p>\n<ol>\n<li>Buttons for increasing\/decreasing the set temperature<\/li>\n<li>Controls for changing the thermostat mode<\/li>\n<li>A switch for changing the fan mode<\/li>\n<li>Display current temperature<\/li>\n<li>Display HVAC status\n<ul>\n<li>When idle, the background turns gray<\/li>\n<li>When heating, the background turns red<\/li>\n<li>When cooling, the background turns blue<\/li>\n<li>When ventilating, the background turns green<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n<div id=\"attachment_322\" style=\"width: 2570px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-322\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.33-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1600\" class=\"wp-image-322 size-full\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.33-PM.png 2560w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.33-PM-300x188.png 300w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.33-PM-768x480.png 768w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.33-PM-1024x640.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-322\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Thermostat Web App &#8211; Idle<\/p><\/div>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_327\" style=\"width: 2570px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-327\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.00-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1600\" class=\"size-full wp-image-327\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.00-PM.png 2560w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.00-PM-300x188.png 300w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.00-PM-768x480.png 768w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.00-PM-1024x640.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-327\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Thermostat Web App &#8211; Heating<\/p><\/div>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_328\" style=\"width: 2570px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-328\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.15-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1600\" class=\"size-full wp-image-328\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.15-PM.png 2560w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.15-PM-300x188.png 300w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.15-PM-768x480.png 768w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-5.47.15-PM-1024x640.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-328\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Thermostat Web App &#8211; Cooling<\/p><\/div>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_329\" style=\"width: 2570px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-329\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-6.46.37-PM.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1600\" class=\"wp-image-329 size-full\" srcset=\"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-6.46.37-PM.png 2560w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-6.46.37-PM-300x188.png 300w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-6.46.37-PM-768x480.png 768w, https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/04\/Screen-Shot-2018-04-11-at-6.46.37-PM-1024x640.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-329\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Thermostat Web App &#8211; Ventilating<\/p><\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>A web-based interface for controlling the IoT thermostat The API-based IoT thermostat system I have been working on has four main components: HVAC Controller, Software and API Temperature Sensor, Software, and API Thermostat Logic, and API Interface for controlling thermostat This post is about the fourth and final component: the [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[8],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/321"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=321"}],"version-history":[{"count":4,"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/321\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":330,"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/321\/revisions\/330"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=321"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=321"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/zachbrogan.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=321"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}